At this point, both R and RStudio should be downloaded on your personal machine. Letâs set up a file system for this course and make sure you can connect to it via âworking directoriesâ.

Question 3

Copy and paste the following vector into R: vec <- sample(1:100, 10, FALSE)

  1. Print vec to the console.
  2. Print the first 5 elements of vec.
  3. Print the last 3 elements of vec.
  4. Print the 3rd and 8th elements of vec.
  5. Print the elements of vec that are larger than 50.
  6. Print the elements of vec that are odd.
Code 
# Part a.
vec <- sample(1:100, 10, FALSE)
vec # You can also do: cat("Part A:", vec)
# Part b.
vec[1:5]
# Part c.
vec[length(vec) - c(2:0)] # There are many ways to do this.
# Example: vec[8:10]; rev(vec)[1:3]
# Part d.
vec[c(3, 8)]
# Part e.
vec[vec > 50]
# Part f.
vec[vec %% 2 == 0]
Output 
 [1]  4 48 51 80 94 13 30 95 99 23
[1]  4 48 51 80 94
[1] 95 99 23
[1] 51 95
[1] 51 80 94 95 99
[1]  4 48 80 94 30

Question 4

Read in Elderton and Pearsonâs (1910) data on drinking and wages using read.csv() and save it as DrinksWages.3 4

  1. Print the column names of DrinksWages.
  2. What type of measurement (Nominal, Ordinal, Interval, or Ratio) is sober? Explain why.
  3. What portion of wages are larger than 30?
  4. Create a new variable inside DrinksWages called total that is the sum of sober and drinks.
  5. Create a new variable inside DrinksWages called x that is drinks divided by x. What is an interpretation of x?
  6. Plot x on the \(X\)-axis and wages on the \(Y\)-axis. Make each class a different color. Use pch = 19. Label your axes appropriately.
Code 
DrinksWages <- read.csv("https://vincentarelbundock.github.io/Rdatasets/csv/HistData/DrinksWages.csv")
# Part a.
cat("Column names of DrinksWages:\n")
Output 
Column names of DrinksWages:
Code 
colnames(DrinksWages); cat("\r")
Output 
[1] "X"      "class"  "trade"  "sober"  "drinks" "wage"   "n"
Code 
# Part b.
mean(DrinksWages$wage > 30)
Output 
[1] 0.3285714
Code 
# Part c.
DrinksWages$total <- DrinksWages$sober + DrinksWages$drinks
# Part d.
DrinksWages$x <- DrinksWages$drinks / DrinksWages$total
# Part e.
colors <- rep("tomato", nrow(DrinksWages))
colors[DrinksWages$class == "A"] <- "dodgerblue"
colors[DrinksWages$class == "B"] <- "orchid"
plot(DrinksWages$x, DrinksWages$wage, col = colors,
     xlab = "Fraction of Workers Who Report Drinking",
     ylab = "Wages", pch = 19, las = 1)
Plot

  1. Make a plot where year is on the x-axis and total math is on the y-axis. Make sure to convert the total math variable to numeric. Be sure to label the axes. Color the plot where all years after 1999 are a different color than pre-2000. Be an artist.
Code 
sat_df$total_math <- as.numeric(sat_df$total_math)
sat_df$color <- "goldenrod"
sat_df$color[sat_df$year > 1999] <- "mediumseagreen"
par(mar = c(4.1, 4.1, 1.1, 4.1)) # setting plot margins, aesthetics
plot(sat_df$year, sat_df$total_math, xlab = "Year", ylab = "Math Score",
     col = sat_df$color, las = 1, pch = 19)
Plot
  1. Remove the rows where total math is missing. Also, remove the columns between year and total math, and everything after total math.

is.na(sat_df$total_math) # this tells which observations are missing
